<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_04.gif"><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/clear.gif" height=35 width=1></td>
<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/swccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Post-Rotel Condition Removal<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(3.50)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10914'>reed "Reedimus" herreid</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10914&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> July 3, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Condition removal is one of the most important strategies to consider in the Lotr ccg, especially now, with the release of Rotel and all of the new citadel cards tempting people to design their decks around.  You will either have to find a way to work around these conditions or eradicate them; this article is here to help you do the latter.  Here is a list of all of the cards available to you, on both the fellowship and shadow sides, and a short evaluation of each.<br>
<br>
Fellowship:<br>
<br>
Dwarf:<br>
<br>
-Make light of burdens.  <br>
TC: 1, Condition, Rare<br>
Plays to your support area.<br>
Maneuver: exert a dwarf companion and discard the top 3 cards from your draw deck to discard either a shadow condition from a dwarf or a weather condition.<br>
<br>
If this card were from any other culture it would be considered a terrible card and would almost never see play.  But, being as dwarves have very few options for removing conditions on their own, many dwarf decks include it.  TC of 1 makes it cheap to get out, but to actually get rid of a condition you need to exert a dwarf companion and discard the top 3 cards from your draw deck.  Ouch.  And with all that, you still cant discard a condition from your opponents support area or from a non-dwarf companion.  Very limited.<br>
<br>
-Song of Durin<br>
TC: 0, Condition, Uncommon<br>
Tale.  To play, exert a dwarf, plays to your support area.<br>
The twilight cost of each [moria] weapon is +2.<br>
Fellowship: Discard this condition to discard up to 2 [moria] conditions.<br>
<br>
This card is huge!  A tale for Gloin to get pumped by, a huge kink in almost every moria decks strategy (scimitar/armory combo more difficult), and if you happen to draw 2 you can use your extra one to get rid of those irritating moria conditions.  The only drawback is that the card is pretty much useless against any culture other than moria.  For playing more than one copy it would be best to also include Bilbo, well spoken gentlehobbit, so you can at least discard it to your advantage.  This card makes dwarves much more attractive.  <br>
<br>
Elf:<br>
<br>
-Seen and the unseen<br>
TC: 0, Event, Common<br>
Fellowship: Exert 2 elves to discard a condition.<br>
<br>
Secret sentinels is generally preferred, and in all but a few situations would be included over this card.  The only reasons to go with this card would be if you already have 4 secret sentinels and for some reason want more, you dont want to pay the 2 twilight of secret sentinels, you dont have any elf allies (and you do have 2 elf companions), you have some reason for wanting to do your condition discarding in the fellowship phase as opposed to the maneuver phase, or you cant afford secret sentinels (SS is a rare, seen and unseen is common).  In all situation other than these, forget about this card.<br>
<br>
-Stand alone against darkness<br>
TC: 1, Event, Uncommon<br>
Maneuver: Exert an Elf to discard a [sauron] minion, a [sauron] condition, or a [sauron] possession.<br>
<br>
Not much to say for this card.  Its great if you happen to be playing against a Sauron deck, useless if youre not.  Probably too conditional to see much play.<br>
<br>
-Secret sentinels<br>
TC: 2, Event, Rare<br>
Maneuver: Exert an Elf ally to discard a condition (or 2 conditions if you spot an Orc).<br>
<br>
One of the best condition removal cards in the game.  Can remove any condition, good chance of removing 2.  The twilight cost is a bit high, but that isnt such a big deal in the maneuver phase.  Only drawback is that you need an Elf ally to do it.  If youve got elf allies, this is almost as good as it gets.<br>
<br>
-Vilya<br>
TC: 0, Artifact ring, Rare<br>
Vit: +1<br>
Bearer must be Elrond.<br>
Maneuver: exert elrond twice and spot a shadow condition to return that condition to its owners hand.<br>
<br>
This card is huge!  Even better than secret sentinels (but that doesnt mean you shouldnt also have secret sentinels).  So many benefits, where to start.  Well, for a twilight cost of zero and a vitality of +1 to Elrond alone some people would play with this card.  Why not?  On lord of rivendell you can use the extra vitality to just draw another card anyway.  Sometimes bouncing a condition back to someones hand is even better than discarding it.  Youll not only clog your opponents hand, but theyll have to pay for the condition again to put it back out.  And if it has a high twilight cost that requires an exertion theyll probably discard it rather than try to keep it out.  Drawback: you need Elrond.  <br>
<br>
Gandalf:<br>
<br>
-Albert Dreary<br>
TC: 1, ally home 1 man, Rare<br>
Str: 3, Vit: 3<br>
To play, spot Gandalf.<br>
Maneuver: exert Albert Dreary to discard a [isengard] or [moria] condition.<br>
<br>
A pretty good card for condition removal.  Getting rid of two conditions for 1 card and 1 twilight is good.  Drawbacks preventing it from seeing too much play are that you need to spot Gandalf and it is limited to only 2 cultures.  But if your local meta includes lots of isengard and moria (whose doesnt?) and you happen to have a consistently appearing <br>
Gandalf, put in an Albert dreary.<br>
<br>
-Sleep, caradhras<br>
TC: 3, event, common<br>
Spell.<br>
Fellowship: Exert Gandalf to discard every condition.<br>
<br>
The ultimate in condition discarding.  You pay a lot (losing o elbereth can be significant), but you get a lot.  If you have Gandalf you need at least one of these, unless your own conditions are too precious to lose, in which case you need... (see next card)<br>
<br>
-Deep in thought<br>
TC: 4, event, Common<br>
Spell.<br>
Maneuver: Spot Gandalf and 4 twilight tokens to discard all shadow conditions.<br>
<br>
A card worthy of challenging Sleep for title of best anti-condition card.  A little more difficult to get it into play (youll have to figure out how to get those 4 twilight in the pool) but the effect is *much* better.  Now you dont need to exert Gandalf, lose your own conditions, or give your opponent extra twilight for their shadow phase.  Expect to see a lot of people replacing a sleep with one of these.<br>
<br>
Gondor:<br>
<br>
-Athelas<br>
TC: 1, possession, Uncommon<br>
Bearer must be a [gondor] man.<br>
Fellowship: discard this possession to heal a companion or to remove a shadow condition from a companion.<br>
<br>
Limited in its ability to remove conditions, as some of the worst conditions are the ones in your opponents support area, but has the benefit of being able to heal a companion in case you dont have any conditions to remove.  More importantly, you can get it out of your hand until you need it.  A decent card.<br>
<br>
Shire:<br>
<br>
-Bilbo, well-spoken gentlehobbit.<br>
TC: 2, ally home 1 hobbit, Uncommon<br>
Str: 2, Vit: 3<br>
Fellowship: exert Bilbo and discard a tale to discard a shadow condition from an opponents support area.  <br>
<br>
Dont play Gandalf or Elves?  Then you probably have this guy in your deck.  Great for tale intensive cultures with few other condition removal options (hobbits and dwarves).  This card is open to many combos too, such as consorting with wizards.  <br>
<br>
<br>
Shadow:<br>
<br>
Moria:<br>
<br>
-Goblin warrior<br>
TC: 2, minion orc, Common<br>
Str: 6, vit: 1, non-roaming: 4<br>
When you play this minion, you may discard a [dwarf] ally or a [dwarf] condition.<br>
<br>
Expect to see this card more now with Rotel out.  Song of During pretty much screws moria over, and this is an easy way for moria to get rid of it.  Opponents not playing Dwarven conditions?  Just get rid of Thrarin then.  This card still has some use against many decks other than all dwarf decks.  -1 str to Fots could be nice.<br>
<br>
-Goblin scrabbler<br>
TC: 1, minion orc, Common<br>
Str: 4, vit: 1, non-roaming: 4<br>
When you play this minion, you may discard an [elf] condition.<br>
The roaming penalty for each [moria] orc you play is -1.<br>
<br>
A good card if you get to discard that Elven condition.  Otherwise, the minus 1 to the roaming penalty is ok.  If your meta has a lot of Elven conditions put this guy in, otherwise might not be so good.<br>
<br>
Isengard:<br>
<br>
-Saruman&#39;s power<br>
TC: 2, event, uncommon<br>
Spell.<br>
Shadow: exert a [isengard] minion to discard all condtions.  <br>
<br>
Sarumans very own version of Sleep.  Great card, so long as youre not playing a lot of conditions yourself.  Not much else to say about it.  This card totally screws dwarf decks.<br>
<br>
Ringwraith:<br>
<br>
-Beauty is fading<br>
TC: 5, event, rare<br>
Maneuver: Exert a Nazgul to discard a free peoples possession or a free peoples condition.  If you can spot no such card, discard an ally or companion (except the ring-bearer) instead.<br>
<br>
If your goal is condition removal, this is probably the last place to look for in attaining it.  Very few people play this card, but sometimes that works to your advantage as you can take your opponent by surprise.  But even taking that into account, the costs are way too high to include this in all but a couple decks.  The only reason I see for playing this would be if you absolutely must get rid of o elbereth and nothing else will work for you, or, more likely, you need to get rid of Thrors map, mirror of Galadriel, or shards of narsil.  This is the only card that will do that.  Good luck trying to get this card to work for you.<br>
<br>
-Pale blade<br>
TC: 2, possession hand weapon, rare<br>
Str: +3<br>
Bearer must be the Witch-king.<br>
He is damage +1.<br>
Response: if the witch-king wins a skirmish, exert him to discard a free peoples condition.<br>
<br>
If youve got a few witch kings, it may be worth putting one of these in there.  The extra strength and damage are nice, and getting rid of o elbereth can mean the game.  Only drawback is that it can be difficult to rely on a combo, but if you are playing nazgul only this might be your best bet.  Either this or (see next card)<br>
<br>
-Stricken dumb<br>
TC: 2, event, rare<br>
Maneuver: exert the witch king to discard a tale or weapon.<br>
<br>
Another way of getting rid of o elbereth, but with the added bonus of being able to get rid of your nazguls other biggest obstacle, the flaming brand.  Both cards cost the same and depend on the witch-king.  Its just a trade off between the strength and damage bonuses of the pale blade or the ability to discard a flaming brand with stricken dumb.  <br>
<br>
Sauron:<br>
<br>
-Curse from mordor<br>
TC: 0, event, uncommon<br>
Shadow: spot a [sauron] orc to discard an [elven] condition<br>
<br>
Not much to say about this card.  Put it in your deck if you really want to get rid of those Elven conditions.  Then hope your opponent is playing them.<br>
<br>
-Shadow&#39;s reach<br>
TC: 1, event, common<br>
Shadow: exert a [sauron] orc to discard a free peoples condition.<br>
<br>
IMHO, most under-rated condition removal card in this list.  Particularly if you are playing Nazgul and are trying to pick between pale blade and stricken dumb.  Throw in some skulkers and this card and your o elbereth problems are over (hopefully).  Nice to be able to discard any condition.  Perhaps saga of elendil on an exhausted rotn that just became defender +2 billion?  I like this card.<br>
<br>
-Orc guard<br>
TC: 1, minion orc, common<br>
Str: 5, Vit: 2<br>
Maneuver: exert this minion and discard your [sauron] condition to discard a free peoples condition.<br>
<br>
Cheap, weak minion, good candidate for enduring evil.  Perhaps make some use out of a condition that isnt helping you.  A card worth considering in some decks.<br>
<br>
-Why shouldn&#39;t I keep it?<br>
TC: 0, event, rare<br>
Manuever: spot a [sauron] minion to discard Bilbo.  The free peoples player may discard 2 free peoples conditions to prevent this.<br>
<br>
Against the right deck, this card would be great.  Get rid of that annoying Bilbo that keeps getting rid of your evil conditions, or at least get rid of some of his fuel (the two conditions).  Probably not a card for every deck though, as your opponent needs to have Bilbo or this card is worthless and will clog your hand.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Thats it.  If you catch something I missed please let me know.  <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
